            "body": "I'm still encountering this issue in the latest Neovim build:\n\n```\nNVIM v0.11.0-dev-1936+g5ee62906a3\nBuild type: RelWithDebInfo\nLuaJIT 2.1.1736781742\n```\n\nI followed the reproduction steps provided by @lucario387 and observed the same behavior. Specifically, when I press `o` on the first line (index 0), the `on_bytes` callback receives a `start_row` value of 1, whereas using `A<Enter>` results in a `start_row` value of 0.\n\nThis discrepancy is causing issues in my workflow. I call `vim.api.nvim_buf_get_text` in the `on_bytes` callback using parameters like this:\n\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_buf_get_text(\n  buf,\n  start_row, -- 0 for `A<Enter>`, 1 for `o`\n  start_col,\n  start_row + new_end_row, -- 0 + 1 for `A<Enter>`, 1 + 1 for `o`\n  (new_end_row == 0) and (start_col + new_end_col) or new_end_col,\n  {}\n)\n```\n\nHowever, pressing `o` on the last line of a buffer results in an `Index out of bounds` error due to the off-by-one error in `start_row`.\n\nIs this discrepancy intentional or is it a bug?",
